  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed global anti-money laundering standards\n- Recommended comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial institution reporting requirements\n- Expanded criminal penalties\n- Improved international information sharing\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Increased digital transaction monitoring\n\n5. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- Risk-based assessment frameworks\n\n6. Global Coordination\n- Increased cross-border collaboration\n- Standardized reporting mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n7. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
